<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Liriomyza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Liriomyza brassicae" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brassicae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Liriomyza brassicae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is difficult to differentiate from 
<taxonomicName family="Hydrangeaceae" genus="L." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="L. sativae" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="sativae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">L. sativae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
externally and has been reared from many of the same plant species. Colour characters can be used to distinguish most individuals, but since there is some overlap in these features, only the male genitalia can be considered authoritative for identification. The dark, cylindrical, and medially constricted distiphallus is most diagnostic for this species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
While this polyphagous leaf-miner is nearly cosmopolitan, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Liriomyza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Liriomyza brassicae" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brassicae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Liriomyza brassicae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not often considered a serious threat to agriculture due to its generally small population sizes (Spencer, 1973a). Several Californian morphotypes that are potentially separate host races or species are not treated here; see 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.2850.1.1" author="Lonsdale, O" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 123" refId="B138" refString="Lonsdale, O, 2011. The Liriomyza (Agromyzidae: Schizophora: Diptera) of California. Zootaxa 2850: 1 - 123, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.2850.1.1" title="The Liriomyza (Agromyzidae: Schizophora: Diptera) of California." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.2850.1.1" volume="2850" year="2011">Lonsdale (2011)</bibRefCitation>
for details.
</paragraph>
